Larson sat down with Keah Brown for Marie Claire to reiterate her position on white men when it comes to her Captain Marvel press tour.

“About a year ago, I started paying attention to what my press days looked like and the critics…

summary: look, when Captain Marvel does well I don’t wanna hear any “Marvel released it in a bad box office month because they wanted it...
body:
look, when Captain Marvel does well I don’t wanna hear any “Marvel released it in a bad box office month because they wanted it to fail” BS like I heard with Black Panther, aight.

Black Panther was released during Black History Month. Captain Marvel is being released during Women’s History Month. Avengers Endgame is being released during April Fool’s Month so we all know that whatever happens in it is “jk, no one’s dead we just messing with you.”

Marvel knows what they’re doing okay.

summary:
Concept for “Avengers Endgame”:
In the final battle of the movie, Hawkeye is killed trying to protect Captain Marvel....
body:
Concept for “Avengers Endgame”:

In the final battle of the movie, Hawkeye is killed trying to protect Captain Marvel. Eventually, Thanos is defeated and the Snap is reversed, leading to a new Avengers lineup.

Then we cut to the mid credits scene. We flash back to the moment when Clint is killed. Carol is grieving for him but this time, we don’t cut back to the battle with Thanos. The scene lingers a bit…until “Clint” reverts back to his Skrull form. Carol is shocked when she realizes that the Skrulls have infiltrated Earth (again). The real Hawkeye is somewhere out there, captured by the Skrulls.

blog.name: positivelydetectivecomics
blog.title: I've Returned For The Moment...
blog.description: Need a place you can discuss your favorite DC stories, films, heroes, and villains without the unnecessary hate? This is the blog for you! This is a place to discuss news and anticipation for upcoming DCEU projects as well as express appreciation for the already existing stories and films we have come to love produced by DC. Marvel fans are welcome to follow just as long as they are civil and respectful towards us. This is a DC fanblog, and while we may offer constructive criticism to what we love, we will not tolerate nonconstructive criticism that only serves to attempt to make what we love less enjoyable. We get enough of that outside of this blog, so we will not tolerate it here.This blog is also ran by a queer Black intersectional feminist.BEFORE YOU FOLLOW, KNOW THIS: I do make posts that discuss and call out fandom racism. I will not sugar coat anything on the subject.
